{
  "case_id": "D2N069",
  "method": "medsum_ent",
  "template": "soap",
  "summary_text": "S:\nThe patient reports right knee pain following a fall while changing a light bulb, describing the pain as primarily in the inside of his knee. He states the pain worsened when bending his knee forward and twisting it. He has been applying ice and taking ibuprofen, but reports minimal relief. He denies any other injuries. He reports a history of afib and has been taking digoxin.\n\nO:\nPhysical exam reveals tenderness to palpation over the medial aspect of the right knee, particularly when applying valgus stress. No fractures are identified on x-ray. There is a small amount of fluid in the knee, but no dislocation. Sensation is intact. The patient's knee range of motion is limited by pain.\n\nA:\nThe patient has an acute medial meniscus sprain or strain, likely secondary to trauma. Examination findings support this diagnosis.\n\nP:\nRescribe a knee brace and instruct the patient to use crutches for two days. Recommend motrin 800 mg every six hours as needed for pain. Schedule a follow-up appointment in one week to reassess and consider an MRI if symptoms do not improve.",
  "reference_summary": "CC:\n\nRight knee pain.\n\nHPI:\n\nMs. Thompson is a 43-year-old female who presents today for an evaluation of right knee pain. She states she was trying to change a lightbulb on a ladder, and she twisted her knee when she stumbled and caught herself from falling yesterday. She has been applying ice and taking Ibuprofen without relief.\n\nCURRENT MEDICATIONS:\n\nIbuprofen, digoxin.\n\nPAST MEDICAL HISTORY:\n\nAtrial fibrillation.\n\nPAST SURGICAL HISTORY:\n\nRhinoplasty.\n\nEXAM\n\nExamination of the right knee shows pain with flexion. Tenderness over the medial joint line. No pain in the calf. Pain with valgus stress. Sensation is intact.\n\nRESULTS\n\nX-rays of the right knee show no obvious signs of acute fracture or dislocation. Mild effusion is noted.\n\nIMPRESSION\n\nRight knee acute medial meniscus sprain.\n\nPLAN\n\nAt this point, I discussed the diagnosis and treatment options with the patient. I have recommended a knee brace. She will take Motrin 800 mg, every 6 hours with food, for two weeks. She will use crutches for the next couple of days. She will follow up with me in 1 week for a repeat evaluation. If she is not better at that time, we will obtain an MRI. All questions were answered.",
